{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01WW7GmFvEMgL1J6UsvUDDdF","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the problem:\n\n1. The `probe.sh` script starts with `sleep 2`, which immediately takes 2 seconds.\n2. The timeout for both liveness and readiness probes is set to `1s`.\n3. Since the probe sleeps for 2 seconds before doing anything, it will always timeout at 1s.\n\nAdditionally, the `mongosh` command to connect to MongoDB also takes some time, so even if we remove the `sleep 2`, the 1s timeout might still be too short.\n\nThe fix should be to either:\n1. Remove the `sleep 2` from the probe script\n2. OR increase the timeout in the probe configuration\n\nThe `sleep 2` appears intentional—likely to give mongosh time to connect—but it directly conflicts with the 1-second timeout. So I need to both remove that sleep and bump up the probe timeouts to something more realistic like 5-10 seconds for liveness and 5 seconds for readiness.\n\nThe failure threshold of 2 is also problematic—that's too aggressive for a pod that might need extra time during startup. I should increase that too.\n\nNow I'm checking the secret mounting more carefully. The probe script references `/etc/health/health-password`, but the secret key is just `password`, so it would actually be mounted at `/etc/health/password`. That's a mismatch that would cause the probe to fail immediately. `/etc/health/password`. But the script reads from `/etc/health/health-password`, which is a mismatch. I'm also noticing the probe has a `sleep 2` at the start but the timeout is only 1 second, so it's timing out immediately. Let me check the StatefulSet configuration to see the full probe setup.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":798,"cache_read_input_tokens":31512,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_t