{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_014WoJhGr2NdHCHa9jRTPxEJ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I can see:\n1. MongoDB is running (`mongod` is process 1) but liveness probe is killing pods because of the timeout issue\n2. The other pods are shutting down (ShutdownInProgress)\n\nSo the pods are cycling. The liveness probe fails (times out) and kills the container, which then restarts.\n\nLet me check what's happening with all pods and check on the econnrefused issue. The `econnrefused` when I ran `mongosh` might be because the port was being used during a restart.\n\nActually, looking more carefully, the ECONNREFUSED might have been because the pod that's currently connecting to port 27017 is currently the probe shutting it down, or the pods are in some cyclic restart state.\nThe restart count shows 0, so the pods haven't actually cycled yet—they're just failing the liveness probe. The ECONNREFUSED error when I tried mongosh is puzzling since mongod is clearly running, so maybe it's listening on a different interface or port than expected.\n\nLooking at the logs more carefully, I'm seeing references to replica set heartbeat failures and other pods shutting down, which points to the liveness probe actively killing pods. Let me check the current state again to see what's actually happening right now.\n\nThe describe output shows repeated probe failures—both readiness and liveness probes timing out after 1 second. With a failure threshold of 2, the pod gets terminated after two consecutive liveness failures, which explains the restart cycle.\n\nThe ECONNREFUSED error I saw could be from the pod restarting and mongod still initializing, or the probe killing the container between when I ran describe and exec. The real issue is that the probe script has a 2-second sleep but the timeout is only 1 second, so it's guaranteed to fail. I need to fix that mismatch first.\n\nMy plan is to remove the sleep from the ConfigMap, then increase all the probe timeouts significantly—bumping the timeout to 5 seconds or more, raising the failure thresholds (6 for readiness, 10 for liveness), and extending the initial delays (60-120 seconds for liveness, 15 seconds for readiness). After the probes stabilize, I'll check if the replica set is initialized and create the health-user if needed. The real issue is that fixing the probe settings will restart the pods, and if the replica set isn't initialized yet, the health check will fail because it depends on the `health-user` existing. So I need to prioritize fixing the probe configuration first to stop the constant pod cycling, then once they stabilize, initialize the replica set and create the necessary users. The plan is to disable the problematic probes, wait for the pods to stabilize, then check if the replica set needs initialization or if the health-user account needs to be created. Looking at the StatefulSet events, I can see the pods are cycling through creation and deletion, which confirms the probe restarts are the core issue.\n\nI'll update the ConfigMap to remove the sleep delay and simplify the health check script, then patch the StatefulSet with more lenient probe thresholds—giving the liveness probe a 60-second initial delay and allowing up to 6 consecutive failures before restarting. Step 3 is deleting the pods to force a restart, though patching the StatefulSet should trigger a rolling update automatically anyway. After the pods come back up, I'll need to verify the replica set status and initialize it if it doesn't exist, then check whether the health-user account needs to be created. Let me start executing these fixes.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3640,"cache_read_input_tokens":36548,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3640},"output_tokens":25,"service_tier":"standard"